    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Hypercalcemia of Malignancy: PTHrP & Bisphosphonates", content: "The nurse practitioner manages Hypercalcemia of Malignancy: PTHrP & Bisphosphonates through understanding of tumor biology, staging systems, and supportive care for cancer patients. Assessment includes comprehensive history (constitutional symptoms, pain, functional status using ECOG or Karnofsky scale, psychological distress screening), physical examination targeting primary tumor site and common metastatic locations, and interpretation of diagnostic studies (tumor markers, imaging for staging, pathology reports including histological grade and biomarker status). The NP applies the TNM staging system to guide prognosis and treatment planning, manages treatment-related toxicities (chemotherapy-induced nausea/vomiting using antiemetic protocols, neutropenic fever management with risk stratification and empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics, mucositis, neuropathy, cardiotoxicity monitoring), prescribes supportive medications (growth factor support, pain management including opioid prescribing and rotation), screens for oncologic emergencies (tumor lysis syndrome, hypercalcemia of malignancy, spinal cord compression, superior vena cava syndrome, febrile neutropenia), and coordinates survivorship care. The NP provides psychosocial support, facilitates advance care planning discussions, manages comorbidities in the context of active cancer treatment, and coordinates multidisciplinary care with oncology, radiation therapy, palliative care, and surgical teams." },
